<div id="stitle" style="display:none;">Notebook Entry</div>
<dl id="n34004g"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n34" href="#n34004g">N34 (VI.B.27)</a>:  <a href="../../ff/fnbs/n34all.htm#n34004g"> 4(g)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> commensurate</blockquote> <dd class="well"> <blockquote class="sources">Christ &hellip; became man in two natures, which internally and inseparably united make One Person, and &hellip; has obtained for man <font color="green">[born with a corrupt basis]</font> reconciliation with God, and eternal life, inasmuch as He by His vicarious death has made satisfaction to God for the world&apos;s sins, and this satisfaction was <font size="-1">PERFECTLY <mark>COMMENSURATE</mark> WITH THE SINS OF THE WORLD</font>. <small> &ldquo;ORTHODOX EASTERN CHURCH&rdquo; <a name="EBOEC" href="../../ff/fdra/fdex.htm#EBOEC"><cite title="source">Encyclopaedia Britannica</cite></a>, 11th edit. (1911) 336 [Comparison of Orthodox, Roman and Protestant doctrine [NOTE. Small capitals denote differences of the Greek Orthodox doctrine from Roman Catholic, italics differences from Protestant doctrines.]]</small></blockquote> </dd></dl>
